annotation.TEXT: This was the longtime slogan for Dial soap.
Steven Seagal is a martial artist and tough-guy actor who has appeared in such action films as Hard to Kill and Under Siege.
Actor David Hedison is best known for playing Captain Lee Crane on the TV series Voyage to the Bottom of the Sea.
Did we miss any references? Let us know in the comments!
Eddie Munster was the young son on the TV series The Munsters. He was played by Butch Patrick.
Devo is a geek-rock proto-new-wave band known for their bizarre costumes (such as the flowerpot hat) and stage antics.
Zsa Zsa Gabor is a socialite and actress, but she’s better known for having had nine husbands.
The Kmart slogan “The saving place” dates back to the ‘70s.
The Shriners are a fraternal organization known for their circuses, good works, and silly-looking fezzes.
Grecian Formula is a hair dye for men that promises to gradually get rid of gray hair over a period of weeks.
A paraphrase of a line from the movie The Abyss, spoken by Ed Harris as he’s trying to resuscitate the drowned Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio.
The announcer for Cops, the long-running reality TV show, says during the opening, “Cops is filmed on location with the men and women of law enforcement.”
Jiffy Lube is a chain of oil-change centers with thousands of franchises nationwide.
A reference to the 19th-century Norwegian fairy tale “Three Billy Goats Gruff.”
The novel (and film) Seven Days in May tells of a planned coup by the U.S. military to avoid disarmament under a treaty with the USSR.
A paraphrased line from the end of Charles Dickens’ novel A Tale of Two Cities; the man who says it is going to his death, sacrificing himself in place of another man.
This is a snippet from the theme song to Love, American Style.
A classic Three Stooges routine, in which they pop out from behind one another, each saying hello in turn.
This is the first appearance of the immortal “Sandy Frank Song.”
The theme, which accompanies the gun barrel sequence, was written by Monty Norman and arranged by John Barry.
Urban legend has it that animator Walt Disney was cryonically frozen after his death; in fact he was cremated.
The Dungeons & Dragons role-playing game uses variously shaped dice to determine events as the adventure unfolds.
This might be foreshadowing, but the Mads present the Cheese Phone in their invention exchange in Episode 313, Earth vs. the Spider.
The American Tourister luggage company ran ads for 15 years in which a gorilla trashed one of their suitcases to show how durable it was.
White Castle is a chain of fast food burger restaurants. Its burgers are also available through vending machines and in the frozen food sections of grocery stores.
Lassie was a hyperintelligent collie who starred in an eponymous TV series for 20 years, as well as a series of movies.
Depend undergarments are a brand of adult incontinence products.
The Three Stooges were a comedy trio that appeared in more than 200 short films. They were known for extreme, often violent slapstick comedy.
Splatball is an indoor paintball arena that has operated in Minneapolis since 1984.
A line from the chorus to “Johnny B. Goode.”
Silence of the Lambs is a horror film about a young FBI agent and her relationship with an imprisoned serial killer, Hannibal Lecter.
From the classic Xmas song “White Christmas,” written by Irving Berlin in the early ‘40s.
Dr. Zaius was one of the intelligent apes in Planet of the Apes; the part was played by Maurice Evans.
The Sasquatch, a.k.a. Bigfoot, is a legendary ape-like creature that supposedly haunts the Pacific Northwest and western Canada.
Joel has pulled off Crow’s arm a couple of times, usually as punishment for a bad joke. In Episode 304, Gamera vs. Barugon, Joel removed Crow's arm for using a horrible pun.
“Good fences make good neighbours” is a line from the Robert Frost poem “Mending Wall.”
Keith Richards is the lead guitarist for the Rolling Stones. He has had widely publicized problems with drug addiction, particularly heroin.
An old ad slogan for McDonald’s McDLT burger, which came in a two-sided container that separated the hot and cold components.
The Fillmore is a legendary concert venue in San Francisco, with fantastic light shows, that hosted some of the biggest bands of the ‘60s.
This musical cue, called “Mysterioso Pizzicato,” dates back to the silent movie era.
An Officer and a Gentleman is a film starring Richard Gere as a young man struggling to become a Navy pilot.
Pop singer Sheena Easton used this line in a series of ads shilling Bally Fitness Center’s “30 Minute Workout.”
“Johnny One Note” is a song from the musical Babes in Arms. Emenee Industries made several electric reed organs in the late ‘60s.
Certs are a brand of breath mints; “Get Certs, get closer” is an ad slogan for Certs from the early ‘80s.
Writer William Burroughs was one of the key writers of the Beat era and an enthusiastic user of drugs, especially heroin.
A Time-Life ad for their series of Old West books talked about a man (one John Wesley Hardin) who was “so mean he once shot a man just for snoring.”
The Minneapolis musician Prince was one of the seminal musical talents of the ‘80s. True to his album Purple Rain, he often wore purple.
Although a celebrated writer, Wilde ended badly: accused of sodomy and sentenced to two years of hard labor. He died a few years after his release from prison.
The Emerald Forest is a film about a man searching for his lost son in the rain forests of Brazil.
Corn dodgers are a traditional southern recipe consisting of dollops of cornbread batter fried in oil.
"Run Through the Jungle" is a 1970 Creedence Clearwater Revival song.
“If living with Obsession is a sin, let me be guilty” is a tagline from a late ‘80s Obsession ad.
On the final round of the TV game show What’s My Line?, the panel would be blindfolded before a celebrity “mystery guest” would enter and sign their name on a chalkboard.
A Bloody Mary is a cocktail consisting of vodka, tomato juice, and a bunch of spices and flavorings, garnished with a stalk of celery.
A paraphrase of the Simon and Garfunkel song “Homeward Bound.”
A famous line from the camp horror classic The Evil Dead.
The Blue & the Gray was a 1982 TV miniseries that related events of the Civil War through the experiences of a war correspondent.
“Feel the earth move” as a metaphor for good sex comes from the Ernest Hemingway novel For Whom the Bell Tolls.
Unfortunately for American Tourister, many people remember it as being a Samsonite commercial.
Eggo is a brand of frozen waffles made by Kellogg’s that can be heated up in the toaster.
Probably a reference to the cat on the animated TV series The Simpsons, which first aired in 1989.
“Spudboys” is an affectionate term for both Devo fans and band members. It comes from a line in the song “Smart Patrol/Mr. DNA.”
Zippy the Chimp appeared on shows as diverse as Howdy Doody, Ed Sullivan, The Price Is Right, and Late Night with David Letterman.
Actor Hal Holbrook was known for playing the white-suited Mark Twain in one-man shows; he also starred in the 1974 TV miniseries Lincoln.
A paraphrase of a line from the movie Apocalypse Now: “Saigon. Shit! I’m still only in Saigon.”
Actor Ricky Schroder debuted in The Champ, a film about a retired boxer who stages a comeback to provide for his son (Schroder).
The Miracle Worker is a teleplay by William Gibson about Ann Sullivan and her deaf and blind pupil, Helen Keller. It became an acclaimed film in 1962.
Donovan was a British folk singer popular in the ‘60s, with such hits as “Mellow Yellow.”
Don Cherry was a jazz trumpeter known for his improvisational style. He was a central figure in the world fusion movement.
A reference to the Chuck Berry song “Johnny B. Goode.”
The movie Fantastic Voyage involves a miniaturized submarine inside the left ventricle of a man’s heart.
Prince has a reputation for being controlling, particularly when it comes to his music.
James Bond is the secret agent created by author Ian Fleming; an iconic image in the films shows Bond silhouetted at the center of a gun barrel.
John Boorman was the director of The Emerald Forest.
Bethlehem is a city on the West Bank, significant in the Christian religion as the purported birthplace of Jesus.
Brian De Palma is a director known for violent thrillers such as Scarface. He loves rotating camera shots.
In the ‘80s, BMWs became synonymous with the yuppie crowd, and their nickname for the car, "Beamer," persists to this day.
The Invaders was a ‘60s TV series about a man’s efforts to expose a secret alien invasion. Their promos bragged about ABC’s recent adoption of color.
For years, rumor had it that Frank had pulled his films from circulation on Comedy Central due to the drubbing he took in this episode and others. Not true.
RadioShack is a chain of electronics stores. They declared bankruptcy in 2015.
In Douglas Adams’ Hitchhiker’s Guide to the Galaxy series, characters escape danger by using an electronic thumb to hitch a ride on a passing spaceship.
A line from the Woody Allen movie Take the Money and Run.
In the 15th century, the teenage Joan of Arc, convinced she was divinely inspired, led the French Army against the English. She was ultimately captured and burned at the stake.
Caddyshack was a comedy set in an exclusive golf club. One of the subplots centered on the activities of a mischievous gopher.
Stranger in a Strange Land was the title of Robert A. Heinlein’s best-selling 1961 sci-fi novel. The phrase comes from Exodus 2:22.
I Heard the Owl Call My Name is a novel by Margaret Craven about a young vicar sent to live among the tribes of the Pacific Northwest.
Peter Noone is an English singer and songwriter. He was the front man for the rock band Herman’s Hermits.
The Banana Splits were animal rock musicians on a Saturday morning kiddie show in the late ‘60s.
The Ford Falcon is a discontinued model of car from the Ford Motor Co. A vibraslap is an instrument that uses a wooden ball and box connected by a metal bar to make a rattling noise.
The Misadventures of Sheriff Lobo was a TV series about a corrupt sheriff; it was a spinoff of B. J. and the Bear.
Jean “Toots” Thielemans is a Belgian harmonica player whose music has been heard on many film soundtracks.
Did we miss any? Let us know in the comments.
Roseanne Barr is a comedian who had her own sitcom, called Roseanne, in which she played a blue-collar mother struggling to keep her family together.
A paraphrase of the song “I Feel the Earth Move” by Carole King.
The German company Goebel produces collectible figurines based on the drawings of Sister M.I. Hummel, a Bavarian nun.
A line from the film Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom, when Indy is facing down the cultists on a bridge.
Probably a reference to McGruff the Crime Dog, mascot for the National Crime Prevention Council, who teaches children how to stay safe.
On the TV series Love, American Style, there would be anywhere up to four short vignettes about love with various celebrity guest stars.
On The Tonight Show, actor Ed Ames (Mingo on Daniel Boone) tried throwing a tomahawk and hit the cowboy target right in the crotch.
A line from The Who’s 1965 hit “My Generation.”
“Pop Muzik” was used by U2 in their reviled 1997 PopMart tour.
A long-running ad campaign for C. F. Hathaway’s men’s dress shirts featured the Hathaway Man, a well-dressed aristocrat with an eye patch.
An imitation of Ted Baxter sobbing to his boss, Lou Grant, on The Mary Tyler Moore Show.
An imitation of bumbling Marine Gomer Pyle apologizing to his long-suffering sergeant, Vince Carter, on the TV series Gomer Pyle, U.S.M.C.
Other films distributed by Frank in the US include the Gamera series and the Fugitive Alien saga.
A common trope of time travel stories is when a character ends up becoming his/her own ancestor. Try Heinlein’s “All You Zombies” for an extreme example.
Actors Ruth Buzzi and Jim Nabors appeared together on a kids’ show about a flying saucer in 1975, The Lost Saucer.
In the late ‘80s and early ‘90s, Calvin Klein ran a series of pretentious, artsy Obsession perfume ads.
In 1964 author Ken Kesey drove cross-country in a bus with a group dubbed the Merry Pranksters, throwing wild LSD parties (the drug was then legal).
A line from MST3K Episode 305, Stranded in Space.
Hanuman is a monkey-like deity in the Hindu faith.
Deadwood, SD, was a wild frontier town that boomed during the Black Hills gold rush. Wild Bill Hickok was murdered there.
Buffy and Cissy were two of the orphaned kids on the TV show Family Affair (the third was Jody); the three were cared for by swinging bachelor “Uncle” Bill Davis.
Miles Davis was a trumpeter who played a seminal role in jazz in the ‘50s and ‘60s.
Spam is a canned, processed pork product made by Hormel.
Bedtime for Bonzo is a legendarily bad 1951 movie starring future president Ronald Reagan as a professor who tries to teach a chimp morality.
The Omnitheater is part of the Science Museum of Minnesota in St. Paul.
Sesame Street is a long-running PBS program for preschoolers, which uses puppets, animation, and live actors to teach numbers, letters, etc.
U-Store-It (now called CubeSmart) is a chain of self-storage facilities, boasting around 37,000 locations nationwide.
On What’s My Line?, the “mystery guest” was usually a celebrity who entered the studio and wrote their name on a chalkboard.
From 1949-1982, the illuminated Weatherball used a color code to indicate the weather forecast.
Irwin Allen was the producer behind such TV shows as Lost in Space, The Time Tunnel, and Land of the Giants.
Lieutenant Commander Data (Brent Spiner) was the android crew member on Star Trek: The Next Generation.
A paraphrase of a line in the Neil Simon play The Sunshine Boys, about two feuding vaudevillians.
The Buick Skylark is a model of car made in various forms for 46 years.
In the film The Princess Bride, Inigo Montoya endlessly recites the speech he will give to the man who killed his father: “Hello. My name is Inigo Montoya. You killed my father. Prepare to die.”
Limburger is a semi-soft cheese known for its strong, distinctive odor. Originally produced in Belgium, it is now largely a German cheese.
An imitation of Art Fern, played by Tonight Show host Johnny Carson, which was in turn based on Jackie Gleason’s character Reggie Van Gleason III.
Isaac Asimov was a highly respected sci-fi writer best known for his Foundation trilogy.
Valium is a tranquilizer that was widely prescribed during the ‘70s until patients began experiencing problems with addiction and side effects.
Kevin Murphy said in a recent interview that the episodes stopped airing not because Frank was offended but because they couldn’t afford to renew the rights for the films.
"It's a madhouse! A madhouse!" is a line from Planet of the Apes, spoken by Charlton Heston.
Cost Cutters is a chain of affordable hair salons.
In The Fellowship of the Ring by J.R.R. Tolkien, Gandalf the wizard confronts a demonic creature called a Balrog in the mines of Moria.
A paraphrase of the famous opening narration of the TV anthology series The Outer Limits.
The longtime slogan for Roach Motels is “Roaches check in—but they don’t check out.”
Aqua Velva is a brand of aftershave.
Comedienne Lily Tomlin created the smart-talking 5 year Edith Ann, who ended her long speeches with a raspberry.
Fuzztone was a line of distortion devices made for electric guitars by Gibson primarily in the ‘60s.
CHiPs was a TV series about two motorcycle cops with the California Highway Patrol.
A paraphrase of the Bee Gees song “Stayin’ Alive” from the disco musical Saturday Night Fever.
The “Colonel Bogey March” is one of the most famous marches ever written. It was composed by Kenneth Alford in 1914.
McHale's Navy was a sitcom about a group of bumblers aboard a PT boat in World War II. It starred Ernest Borgnine as Lt. Commander Quinton McHale.
Chuckles is a common name for chimpanzees in fiction; there are several children's books with that as a character, plus a myriad of plush toys.
Play Misty for Me is a film starring Clint Eastwood as a DJ being stalked by an obsessed fan.
A reference to the John Steinbeck short story “Flight.”
“Give a hoot, don’t pollute” was the longtime slogan of Woodsy Owl, the mascot for the US Forest Service since 1970.
A line from the song “Tradition,” from the musical Fiddler on the Roof.
Krakatoa is a volcano in Indonesia that erupted in 1883, destroying most of the volcanic peak and killing roughly 36,000 people.
A paraphrase of Charlton Heston’s final lines from Planet of the Apes.
A variation on the old school field trip standby “Ninety-Nine Bottles of Beer on the Wall.”
Actor Darren McGavin is best known for starring in the TV series Kolchak: The Night Stalker and playing the father in the film A Christmas Story.
John Berryman was a poet and professor of literature; he struggled with depression and alcohol abuse for years before his suicide in 1972.
Lester “Pres” Young was a jazz saxophonist who played with Count Basie and turned Kansas City into a major jazz center in the ‘30s.
The Joshua Light Show is a psychedelic visual effects display used by many bands during shows in the late ‘60s/early ‘70s.
The 1925 trial pitted creationists against evolutionists. A Tennessee high school teacher was found guilty of teaching evolution, but the evolutionists won in the court of public opinion.
Yes. Yes it is.
“Ebony and Ivory” is a hit single by Paul McCartney and Stevie Wonder that commends the piano keyboard as a model of racial harmony.
William Conrad is best remembered as the narrator of Rocky and Bullwinkle and for the detective shows Cannon and Jake and the Fatman.
The Shakiest Gun in the West is a comic western starring Don Knotts as a dentist who unwittingly becomes a gunfighter.
Hickory Farms is a company that specializes in gift baskets of processed meat and dairy products.
A paraphrased line from the Donovan song “Hampstead Incident.”
“I should have taken that left toin at Albukoykee” is a famous catchphrase of Bugs Bunny.
The Dells is a middle American resort in Wisconsin with go carts, miniature golf, water rides, and other wholesome family fun.
Wild at Heart is a film starring Nicolas Cage and Laura Dern as a young couple on the run from hired killers.
Colby is a type of mild cheese similar to cheddar, first produced in Wisconsin about 140 years ago.
The theme song to the ‘60s TV sitcom It's About Time opens with these two lines.
Nair is a brand of hair removal products made by Church & Dwight Co.
Portly character actor Ned Beatty starred in Deliverance, directed by John Boorman. “Fat old hog” refers to a scene in which Beatty's character is raped.
The Lovin’ Spoonful was a pop rock group known for songs like “Do You Believe in Magic” and “Summer in the City.”
An imitation of the folksy narrator from the TV series The Dukes of Hazzard. He was played by country musician Waylon Jennings.
Gamera is a series of Japanese kaiju films about a large flying turtle who befriends children and occasionally stomps Japan.
Hostess Cupcakes are a chocolate snack cake with vanilla cream filling and chocolate icing, with white icing squiggles on top.
In the mid-‘80s there was a craze for an animated teddy bear named Teddy Ruxpin. When you put a special tape cartridge into Teddy, he moved in time to the story on the tape.
A paraphrase of lines in Shakespeare’s Romeo and Juliet: “What’s in a name? That which we call a rose/By any other name would smell as sweet.”
And let us know if we missed any references!
An imitation of Rocky the Flying Squirrel and Bullwinkle from their classic ‘60s animated series.
A variation on a thought experiment from the 18th century: “If a tree falls in the forest, and no one is there to hear it, does it make a sound?”
Batman wears a belt around his waist known as his utility belt, which has pouches containing various gadgets that help in his crusade against crime.
From the 1979 synth-pop atrocity “Pop Muzik,” perpetrated by the English New Wave group M.
Diane Arbus was a photographer renowned for her portraits of people on the fringes of society: strippers, nudists, transvestites, etc.
Glamorous actress Frances Farmer was repeatedly hospitalized for mental illness during the ‘40s.
“Shock the Monkey” is a song by Peter Gabriel.
In Saturday Night Fever, Tony Manero (John Travolta) haunts the disco and dreams of a life outside his native Brooklyn.
A paraphrase of the song “Jolly Holiday” from the musical Mary Poppins.
The Wisconsin Duck Tours offers amphibious tours of the Dells on land and in the Wisconsin River; it has been operating since 1946.
The hokey pokey has its origins in a British folk dance, with variants dating back to the early 19th century.
“Go ahead—make my day” is the iconic line spoken by Dirty Harry Callahan in the film Sudden Impact.
Veg-O-Matic by Ronco is one of the first food processors, released in 1963.
Reese’s Peanut Butter Cups are a candy consisting of a peanut butter filling surrounded by a layer of chocolate.
Actress Vivien Leigh struggled with the bipolar disorder throughout her adult life.
The superbly bearded Fidel Castro was the socialist leader of Cuba from 1959-2008, when he formally transferred power to his brother Raúl.
The punchline to an old joke: when a man is told that a thermos keeps hot things hot and cold things cold, he looks puzzled and asks, “How do it know?”
In addition to the color purple, Prince was fond of ruffled shirts, metallic fabrics, shoulder pads, wide lapels, and other expressions of ‘80s excess.
A paraphrased line from the film Raising Arizona.
“Famous Potatoes” is the slogan that appears on Idaho license plates.
A paraphrase of a line from the Arnold Schwarzenegger film Commando.
Michael Nesmith was one of The Monkees, the ‘60s musical group that had their own TV show from 1966-68.
Neil Peart is the drummer for the progressive rock band Rush.
The slang for a burned body comes from Crispy Critters, a frosted cereal that came in the shapes of various animals.
Uncle Charley, Chip, and Ernie were characters in the sitcom My Three Sons. William “Uncle Charley” Demarest often worked with writer-director Preston Sturges, the father of screwball comedy.
Kmart is a discount store chain started in 1962 by Sebastian Kresge.
This is the war cry of the Daleks.
King Lear is a Shakespeare tragedy about a king driven mad by his daughters’ ingratitude; it has a famous scene in which Lear raves during a storm.
Ron Perlman is a burly actor who played the deformed Vincent on TV’s Beauty and the Beast.
Koko is a gorilla who can famously communicate with humans using signs based on ASL; she knows more than 1,000 signs.
The Stooges’ “hello” routine has been endlessly homaged in pop culture.

Since 1974, rolls of Brawny paper towels have featured the smiling visage of a rugged yet handsome outdoorsman in a red plaid shirt.
In 1963, Jack Ruby fatally shot JFK assassin Lee Harvey Oswald in a crowded Dallas police station while Oswald was being transferred to the county jail.
Waiting for Godot is a play by Samuel Beckett in which two vagrants pass the time waiting for an individual named Godot to show up.
A line from the song “Hello, I Must Be Going,” from the Marx Brothers movie Animal Crackers.
Masons have a number of special handshakes to identify themselves to other members and indicate what rank they hold.
Chief Justice Earl Warren was in charge of investigating the assassination of JFK. The “Lone Gunman” theory is the term for his commission’s conclusion that Oswald acted alone.
Planet of the Apes—which, obviously, this film ripped off—starred Charlton Heston as an astronaut trapped on a world where apes have enslaved humans.
Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein relied on his loyal Republican Guard to suppress dissent in the army and among the civilian population.
"Billy Don't Be a Hero" is a hit single by Paper Lace. Though associated with Vietnam, the lyrics are actually about the Civil War.
In 1972, five men broke into the Democratic Party headquarters in the Watergate office complex; the scandal eventually brought down President Nixon.
Serial killer Jame Gumb insisted on lotion because he wanted to make a suit from the skin of his victims.
Tonight Show host Johnny Carson’s famous all-glass Malibu beach home apparently suffered some damage in the 1987 Whittier Narrows earthquake.
The F train is a subway line in Manhattan that runs between Jamaica, Queens, and Coney Island, Brooklyn. It began service in 1940.
Samuel Beckett, the author of Waiting for Godot, always refused to interpret his play, saying, “If I had known more, I would have put it in the text.”
Time of the Apes: Fully annotated by The Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
One (faked) scene in the film Faces of Death showed tourists in Egypt eating monkey brains scooped directly from the skull.
The Globe Theatre was a London playhouse built by William Shakespeare’s theater company in 1599.
Jame Gumb was the serial killer in the film The Silence of the Lambs; he used a van to kidnap his victims.
Characters from the TV show M*A*S*H: B.J. Hunnicutt, Benjamin Franklin “Hawkeye” Pierce, and “Trapper” John McIntyre.
The House on the Rock is a bizarre assemblage of buildings and gardens stuffed full of taxidermy, mannequins, a full-size carousel, etc. It is located in Spring Green, WI.
Zippy the Chimp was a frequent guest on TV variety shows of the ‘50s and '60s.
In the novel (and film) A Clockwork Orange, bands of foppishly dressed thugs called “droogs” roam the streets of a dystopian England.
B. J. and the Bear was a TV series about the adventures of a trucker (B. J.) and his pet chimp (Bear).
A paraphrase from a jingle for the Northwestern National Bank Weatherball in downtown Minneapolis.
This is behavior only seen in captive primates, never in the wild. It seems to be linked to intelligence and highly developed speech centers.
A common question asked of the “mystery guest” on What's My Line?
Steven Tyler is the lead singer for the rock band Aerosmith. He is known for his flamboyant style and large mouth.
Sandy Frank is a film and TV producer who imported, dubbed, and distributed many Japanese films in the ‘60s & ‘70s.
Oscar Wilde was a 19th-century Irish poet and playwright known for his legendary wit.
The 19th-century feud between the Hatfield and McCoy families apparently began with an argument over a hog and escalated until a dozen people had been killed.
A line from the 1975 film Monty Python and the Holy Grail.
A line from MST3K Episode 101, The Crawling Eye.
And Time of the Apes comes to a close
One of Jame Gumb’s lines from The Silence of the Lambs: “It rubs the lotion on its skin or else it gets the hose again.”
Nurse Margaret “Hot Lips” Houlihan and surgeon Frank Burns had a passionate love affair on the TV series M*A*S*H.
“Between love and madness lies ... Obsession” is a slogan dating back to 1985, which is still in use today.
Pablo Picasso is considered by many as the founder of modern art. He painted in many different styles, of which the most famous is Cubism.
Actor William Conrad starred in a series of ads for First Alert smoke detectors during the ‘70s.
A paraphrase of the theme song to Go Go Gophers, a short-lived animated TV series that spun off from Underdog.
A line from late-‘80s TV ads for the Time-Life Books series Mysteries of the Unknown.
“You’re soaking in it” was the slogan in a series of ads for Palmolive dish soap that ran for 25 years.
Lancelot Link, Secret Chimp was a Saturday morning, live-action program featuring chimps with dubbed voices in a Get Smart-style spy comedy.
Smokey Bear is the mascot for the U.S. Forest Service. He was created to push fire prevention, with the slogan “Only you can prevent wildfires.”
Issey Miyake is a Japanese fashion designer known for his high-tech designs.
Davy Crockett: King of the Wild Frontier is a film starring Fess Parker as the legendary outdoorsman.
“Horse” is a slang term for heroin. “A monkey on your back” is a slang term for drug addiction.
A reference to the Al Green song “Let’s Stay Together.”
A line in the film Patton, spoken by George C. Scott: “Rommel, you magnificent bastard, I read your book!”
A paraphrase of Sting’s maniacally over-the-top line in 1984’s Dune, “I WILL kill him!”
The Wackiest Ship in the Army is a film (and later a short-lived TV series) about a ship full of misfits during World War II.
“The owls are not what they seem” is a well-known line from the surreal TV series Twin Peaks.
Hostess Sno Balls are a type of cream-filled snack cake covered with a layer of marshmallow frosting and coconut.
“Excuse me, are those Bugle Boy jeans that you’re wearing?” is an old ad slogan for Bugle Boy jeans.
With annotations provided by The Annotated MST website.
A famous line from the Peter Falk/Alan Arkin movie The In-Laws: “Serpentine, Sheldon, serpentine!”
Colonel Harland Sanders came up with the famous “original recipe” and founded Kentucky Fried Chicken. He died in 1980.
“I’ve Got a Lovely Bunch of Coconuts” was a hit for both Merv Griffin and Danny Kaye in the ‘50s.
Ponderosa was the name of the ranch on the TV show Bonanza. Eric “Hoss” Cartwright was the middle son of the ranch owner.
In the 1992 Academy Awards, Lambs became only the third film to win Oscars in all top five categories.
An imitation of the Three Stooges’ Curly Howard (Jerome Horwitz).
Roseanne attracted heavy criticism for her deliberately awful rendition of the national anthem in 1990.
The longtime ad slogan for the Rug Doctor brand of carpet steam-cleaning machines is “Steamin’ mad at dirt!”
Now you can learn the truth behind all the references, even the ones that don't involve human-like apes.
A reference to the classic kids’ song “Hokey Pokey.”
Freemasonry, or the Masons, is a secret fraternal organization with about 5 million members. Their meeting places are called temples.
Pizza rolls are a frozen delicacy similar to egg rolls, but in pizza flavors. They are made by Totino.
Anthony Braxton is an avant-garde composer and musician who uses diagrams for the titles of his works.
This presentation was brought to you by the Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
A reference to Lucille Ball, star of I Love Lucy and The Lucy Show. A screwdriver is a drink made of vodka and orange juice.
This is an annual fund-raiser that began in 1950; instead of collecting candy, kids collect money for the children’s advocacy group.
Sketches of Spain is a 1960 album by jazz trumpeter Miles Davis.
Sandy Frank also produced the hit game show Name That Tune.
The Daleks are a race of alien creatures housed within mechanical devices on the British TV series Doctor Who.
An imitation of Patty Duke as Helen Keller in The Miracle Worker.
In 1989, Gabor got into a legal kerfuffle when she slapped a Beverly Hills police officer after he pulled her over for a traffic stop.
Wal-Mart is one of the largest companies in the world.
